My opinion on the dividend discussion here in the comments:

If you are looking to retire on your dividend portfolio in less than 5 years, microsoft would probably not be the best choice, because you dont have enough time to proit from the potential massive dividend growth. Especially if you are 50 or older, and looking at around 30 years of life left.

On the other hand if you are in your 20s or 30s and plan to retire in 20+ years, you have the time to wait for microsoft to increase the dividend payment, probably outgrowing titles like AT&T in that time span and hopefully keep growing in your retirement.

I personaly am in my late twenties and own both dividend growth and dividend yield stocks.
I like to have yields stocks like AT&T because the cashflow motivates me and can be used flexible to reinvest im the same company or invest in other opportunities.
I also like to own dividend growth stocks like microsoft where the yield on cost is improving rapidly over the years.

Be glad you can only invest into Microsoft and not Xbox specifically, Microsoft is the far wiser investment. The launches of the the Xbox Series X and Xbox Series S has largely been mishandled and rushed, and the GamePass system has been a cataclysmic failure with server side issues that have rendered the service unusable for many. Not to mention, the structure of a streaming service like Netflix doesn't jive well with Video Game content... Letting people play full Triple AAA games that took years to develop for nothing but a flat monthly fee instead of an individual purchase is a finacial death sentence to small and medium game developers of all kinds, and many are only on the GamePass platform because Microsoft has essentially bribed them to be on their platform, at cost.

The Xbox division is essentially sinking money into GamePass by paying developers to use their platform, and they're hoping it will get enough viewer/player engagement to balance out the cost of providing the service... but in my opinion, it is not a sustainable model, and will probably be fundamentally changed or even scrapped later on. 

Its also worth noting that even though Microsoft is the bigger and more advanced company, Xbox is technologically behind its main competitors, Nintendo and Sony. Nintendo's Switch tablet style design and motion control has synergized with the mobile gaming demographic incredibly well in addition to expanding and solidifying their own loyal consumer base, and Sony's PS5 has graphic capability and processing power that, so far, seems to have badly outperformed both the Series S and Series X in both regards.

Xbox consistently dominated the 7th generation of console gaming with the 360, and they performed moderately well in the 8th generation as well... but we're moving into the 9th generation of gaming consoles now and so far Xbox has severely underperformed while PS5 has been almost impossible to obtain because of its insanely high demand.

My feeling is that Xbox will not perform well this generation, and this will result in them either diminishing their gaming sector or doubling down on innovations for the next gen... but the next gen will be some time from now.

A common thing for everything that Microsoft does... It's business branches that have barely any customer volatility.
The main competition is for new customers. And in some instances, even then it's more or less a matter or priority vs competition.

Either you choose to go OSX.. or Windows. And once you are on a platform, there's barely any switching. Especially for companies.
With Office... The Apple-version is pretty much limited to the Apple-Ecosystem, the only competition to it is Google-Docs. And then it's unlikely to change for quite a while. In case of companies, they're already invested in Azure at this point and likely to get other Azure services (instead of going to the competition) for ease of management, integration benefits, etc.
Yes, AWS does some things better than Azure, and for those things it's an incentive to go hybrid between clouds. But there's always to option for MS to satisfy that ressource-demand with the aforementioned benefits.
And the same goes for pretty much all of their cash-cows.
Since almost any change in IT-Systems also has the almost guaranteed potential to also cause a change in organization structure and/or at least business processes, the cost to change is substantial, so the barrier to switch is pretty high. And for highly demanded applications, there's always integration into their other systems providing very strong incentives to leave the rest as it is. In essence, they do have the same benefits as they'd get from customer loyalty measures... by simply providing a decent and affordable enough alternative to subjectively and objectively better products with that wide of a portfolio. And they have enough funds to outright buy aspiring but unestablished competition... and the cloud ressources to strike a deal and profit from their existance.

The fact that you did a video about MSFT around June last year give us some good perspective of what is behind of every stock price estimation and company valuation. It is a pure guess, and that is alright. We are all guessing here. 

Your´s is an educated guess, it has past performance data supporting it, but at the end of the day you are guessing how much is going to be the growth rate for the next 10 years, and that has a huge impact on your valuation and your expected return. I think the right question here is: What has happened from June 2020 to August 2021 that made you change your EBITDA and FCF growth estimate? 

In your previous video, after five years, growth rate turns a one digit percentage amount. In this one, you keep a two digit EBITDA and Cash growth percentage all the way till 2030. That´s the ultimate reason you end up with such a high price difference between the two analysis. 

Why to change the growht rate percentage so significantly after 2025? Does Microsoft´s performance during last year really justify keeping a 2 digit growth percentage from 2025 till 2030? Is the previous estimate was too conservative? Or is this last estimate too optimistic? 

Last year the stock was trading at 200 USD when you did the video, it was supposed to be 350 USD after 10 years,  and as of now we are at 300 USD. It was a "meh" on your video. Too expensive! Overpriced. Clearly, last year stock performance indicates that your previous estimate was too conservative. 

Will the future stock performance show us this 840 USD estimate is too optimistic? Or will it surpsie us once again? Only time will tell. 

At the end of the day, I think, the exact amounts or final price estimates are not so relevant. Microsoft is a hell of a company. Last 10 years performance is outstading, as you clearly show on your video (kudos to you for that) and they are checking every indicator. They keep growing Revenue, EBITDA, margins, Cash. Not too high CAPEX and repurchasing shares. What else do we want? :D. The same of everything but bigger? The same of everything but cheaper? Can that even be possible? 

They seem to be able to continue performing in the same way in the next years, and then slowly reduce the growth as they become more mature (one would think that they already should be on that post growth phase, as they are bigger than 2 Trillion now, but they keep surprising us).

So yeah, I might wait till next dip or the next big red day in Nasdaq, when everyone is freaking out about godknowswhat, and buy a few shares. Or knowing all this, we can keep waiting till the next big crash or 50% market correction, to get all the upside, and no downside, but nobody knows when that will happen.

One additional question, if you please: One of the first items I seek when I value a company is the price to earnings ratio, then followed by the forward price to earnings ratio. Why do you look for the average 5-year PE ratio? If Microsoft dropped by 50% tomorrow morning, and the PE ratio all the sudden became reasonable, would you still be concerned with the average PE ratio of the last 5 years?
@JMK thanks for clearing that up.
And the forward pe never really made sense to me tbh

The 5 year pe is not the same as the average pe over the last 5 years. It is the CURRENT (so not the average) price, divided by the average earnings of the last 5 years. This way the pe becomes more reliable. For example during covid, some companies saw their earnings drop. This drop is likely to be temporary. By taking the average of earnings, one off events have less impact

With respect to the 60 PE ratio, he is referring to the average price to earnings ratio over the last 5 years.

Shot in the dark, but a serious question - Do you need programmers to build or further develop the everything money app? I have quite a bit of experience with this sort of stuff. Myself and another programmer built a python / django web-based framework that could construct portfolios with various methodologies and rules, selecting an investment universe of shares by country/region/exchange, estimating expected returns or other signals through some sort of regression model, further filtering out the universe based on econometric data, setting constraints, and applying all sorts of weighting methodology. Basically rules-based investing with a tonne of options to construct your portfolio , e.g. for all US listed tickers, estimate a set of expected returns using whatever methodology you like, filter out the worst 25% expected returns, filter out everything that isn't "value", and then apply risk-parity (or inverse vol or prop-weighted, etc) to the remainder and produce a set of weights for the month. You could then backtest the portfolio and run it going forward. The app would also take daily and monthly stock data from csv's produced via Bloomberg and do all sorts of data transformations and inferences, so that one could use this to produce live portfolios. 

I've also been heavily involved in another app which takes a more top down approach to investing, you upload indices and funds and with these you can produce returns or holdings-based attributions of portfolios, you can do an investing style analysis if you have the holdings of the portfolios and see how much you are better on various sectors or by investing styles (e.g. value vs momentum), you can also drawing a 3D feasible set based on a set of uploaded indices and funds and vary how the set was constructed (e.g. does risk concern you or are you actually concerned about tracking error) as well as reporting various risk metrics. Essentially, a tool for multi-fund managers to decide to how allocate "best". It's a very cool app if I don't say so myself. This baby was built in R, which produces very cool graphs and has a lot of useful statistical functions, but not great for a web-based app to be bluntly honest - R is a language built by statisticians and not programmers! However, it runs and is used by (a few) people to allocate money IRL, so hopefully I can toot my horn a little here.

Anyway, I have 1 to 1.5 days free a week and I could always do with a bit more 'free cash flow', "financial programming" is my niche, I like the channel, I like what ya'all are doing - I think I could help enhance your Everything Money app. Is your dev team full / are you even looking to hire remote part-time?

Let me explain how this ends.  Eventually at some point you run out of Buyers, and that will happen.  There will be a lot of bag holders caught at the top. A lot of there bag holders will be on margin accounts... be it on Robin Hood or wherever.  When it does crack stocks go down harder than they go up.  These bag holders (a lot of them) will get margin called.  Prices will drop so fast there will be no buyers to catch it.  ( we call that price gap).  And when you get Margin called and there are no buyers... guess what you may owe your broker money.  Now imagine something like Robinhood having 2 million margin calls with no buyers and now Robinhood is on the hook because they have to actually go collect millions and possibly 100s of millions of dollars from accounts that for margin called and couldn’t get out.  Do you think these people will have the money to pay back Robinhood? Well.. what happens now? Robinhood goes belly up, sends a shockwave through the financial system Bc Robinhood has no money to pay people Bc they had too many margin accounts stuffed all into 1 stock.  Resulting effect mass sell offs and uncertainty across the board.  I real sh^^ fest. Anyway this is only my theory and I am not a financial advisor and this is not financial advice, just my opinion and idea.

EV needs infrastructure.  First on the agenda is power generation for charging.  If every household in the US that have 2 cars is replaced with 2 EV, where is the power infrastructure?   It is not just the power plant, but the power lines, switches and transformers plus home wiring needed to meet this power need.  Faster charging requires heavier power lines and home wiring.  Add to this commercial fleets of trucks, vans, buses and etc.  Every 5 to 10 years the entire battery pack must be replaced.  Lead acid batteries are recycled.  Lithium batteries contain flammable metals and electrolytes.  Needs special storage and handling.  Current cars contain about 100 pounds of copper.  EV need about 800 lbs of copper.  Do we have the copper mines and refineries to meet EV demands.  Lithium is a rare metal.  Do we have enough lithium mines and refineries?    Electric motors use rare earth magnets.  Do we have enough mines and refineries for such materials?  Today our power grid is struggling to meet population growth and energy needs of a digital society.  Imagine what EV will do the grid and current resources.
